  "original_title": "2022 \u0db4\u0dc5\u0db8\u0dd4 \u0d9a\u0dcf\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dad\u0dd4\u0dc0\u0dda\u0daf\u0dd3 \u0d86\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dae\u0dd2\u0d9a\u0dba \u0dc3\u0dd8\u0dab \u0dc0\u0dd9\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "The economy will be negative in the first quarter of 2022",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Sri Lanka's economic growth in the first quarter of 2022 was negative at 1.6 percent, according to the Department of Census and Statistics. Accordingly, Sri Lanka's GDP has declined by 1.6 percent compared to the first quarter of 2021.",
        "At a time when the Sri Lankan economy is recovering sharply after the Kovid epidemics of 2020 and 2021, the economic growth rate in the first quarter of 2022 has been negative. According to the Department of Census and Statistics, economic growth has slowed due to inflation, rupee depreciation, dollar shortfall, declining remittances and tourism revenues. They also reported the highest decline in agricultural activity in the quarter since 2015.",
        "According to the Department of Census and Statistics, there is a significant decline in paddy cultivation. The industrial sector also showed negative economic growth, but the services sector showed modest growth, the department said."
      ],
